The paper deals with algorithms for testing connectivity and bipartiteness of intersection graphs of geometric objects, which is a topic in computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of subquadratic algorithms suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of data structures (cs.DS). The paper also considers lower bounds for connectivity and k-colorability problems, which are topics in discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper discusses the complexity of testing bipartiteness for specific types of geometric objects, such as line segments and balls, which may be of interest to researchers in the sub-category of graph theory (cs.GT).
